04524nam a22006975i 9781442603240DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20192006onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426032407 a10.3138/97814426032402doi  a(DE-B1597)528838  a(OCoLC)1114858044  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aE169.12.B73 2006 7aPOL0400002bisacsh04a327.731 aBrooks, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAs Others See Us :bThe Causes and Consequences of Foreign Perceptions of America /cStephen Brooks. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1. The Three "I's" of Cognitive Isolationism -- tCHAPTER 2. The American Dream Machine -- tCHAPTER 3. Mass and Elite Perceptions of America -- tCHAPTER 4. A Values Gap? -- tCHAPTER 5. Elite Perceptions of America -- tCHAPTER 6. What Drives Anti-Americanism? -- tCHAPTER 7. Why the World's Perceptions Matter -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the ironies of the post-Cold War world, in which the power of the United States is without rival, is that the costs of isolationism and ignorance are greater than ever. The temptation to imagine that the rest of the world matters less than before is enticing, as America basks in the triumphant glow of a world in which capitalism and democracy, under the aegis of American leadership, are thought to have vanquished all rivals. Although it is unlikely that Americans will come to pay much attention to the rest of the world anytime soon—except when their citizens are threatened or killed abroad, or when they are persuaded that the threat of foreigners doing harm at home seems real—their failure to do so cripples the ability of the United States to understand a world in which American interests, security, and prosperity are embedded to an unprecedented degree. As Others See Us investigates the causes and consequences of the world’s perceptions of America. It proceeds from the premise that the images, ideas, and information that foreign populations have of the United States and Americans come from a number of sources, most of which are mediated. Some of these sources are American, Hollywood especially. Others are located outside the country, in the media, educational, religious, and political systems through which foreign populations learn about America. Any attempt to understand the "what" and "why" of foreign perceptions of America needs to look closely at these external determinants of how the image and interpretation of the United States is constructed in different societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnti-Americanism. 0aCivilization, ModernxAmerican influences. 4aCoursebook. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144260324040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442603240423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442603240.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK